SIMPLE: slab
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Slab
<hw>Slab</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>slabbe</ets>,
of uncertain origin; perhaps originally meaning, a smooth piece, and
akin to <ets>slape</ets>, Icel. <ets>sleipr</ets> slippery, and E.
<ets>slip</ets>, v. i.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A thin piece of anything,
especially of marble or other stone, having plane surfaces.</def>
<rj><au>Gwilt.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An outside piece taken from a log or timber in
sawing it into boards, planks, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The wryneck.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>The slack part of a
sail.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Slab line</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a line or
small rope by which seamen haul up the foot of the mainsail or
foresail.</cd> <rj><au>Totten.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slab</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Slab
<hw>Slab</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Gael. & Ir. <ets>slaib</ets> mud,
mire left on a river strand, and E. <ets>slop</ets> puddle.]</ety>
<def>Thick; viscous.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Make the gruel thick and <qex>slab</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slab</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Slab
<hw>Slab</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>That which is slimy or viscous; moist
earth; mud; also, a puddle.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Evelyn.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slabber</ent>⟦br⟧
